Author Classification Using KNN Analysis¶

1. Introduction¶

In this project, I will be using the K Nearest Neighbour (KNN) classification algorithm to analyse the written works of 2 authors. The written works will analysed using the word choice by author (frequencies of words). Two unknown works will be introduced and the KNN method will be used to predict who the author is, from the two known authors.

The KNN classification algorithm measures the distance between the unknown author's data plots and the know authors data plots and selects the k closest points. Where k is a constant. The author with most number of points covered within the k-range is the most likely author of the book.

Author 1 is L. Frank Baum and Author 2 is Nathaniel Hawthorne. I chose this two authors because of their unique areas of focus. Frank's works focus more on religion, morality and history whiles Nathaniel's works focuses more on children's fantasies.

To read more about the KNN algorithm and how it works, you can visit the KNN wikipedia page.

2. Extract Dimensions of Analysis from Literary Works¶

I downloaded six(6) works for each author from Project Gutenberg website and I striped the websites copyright info from the header and footer for each document, this is because I want to access only the authors words.

After I parsed the works using a python program I wrote to get all the uniq words in the file and convert it into a csv file of word and word count frequency.

4. Dimensions of Analysis¶

I will be using the word frequencies as my dimensions of analysis. Word frequency was calculated as $\frac{unique-word-count}{total-word-count}$. I chose to use frequency because each work has a diferrent total number of words. Using the frequency creates a normalized range of (0-1) for all the works, thus, allowing a comparison between other works.

I will be using 3 dimensions of analysis for this project. That is, 3 words; one representing the x-axis, y-axis and z-axis each. Down in the Visualization Section, I will be using these 3 words: x_word="head", y_word = "idea", z_word="looks"

I chose these words because they appeared a reasonable number of times for all the authors.

NB: I may change these words to test other words

7. KNN Analysis¶

Using k values (k=5 and k=7), I will perform a KNN analysis both Unknown A and Unknown B. I first create a distance function (d(x,y,z)) to calculate the 3 dimensional distance between the unknown authors' works and the known. I then append and sort them into a list to get the closests neighbors to the unknown authors (neighbors(label,x,y,z)).
After this, I plot a 3d scatter plot to show the closest k neighbors to the unknown authors.
The author with the most neighbors within the range k is considered the author of the unknown work.

Unknown A

¶

In [18]:
def d(n,x1,y1,z1):
    return np.sqrt((x[n] - x1)**2 + (y[n] - y1)**2 + (z[n] - z1)**2)

def neighbor(label, x1, y1,z1,n):
    return (d(n,x1,y1,z1), x1, y1, z1, label)
In [19]:
neighborsa = [ neighbor("Author A", x[i], y[i], z[i],10) for i in range(5)]
neighborsa += [ neighbor("Author B", x[i], y[i], z[i],10) for i in range(5,10)]

plt.legend(loc="best")
counta=0
countb=0
for i in range(k):
    x1 =[x[10],neighborsa[i][1]]
    y1 = [y[10], neighborsa[i][2]]
    z1 = [z[10], neighborsa[i][3]] 
    if neighborsa[i][4] == "Author A":
        color = "r" 
        counta+=1
    else:
        color = "b"
        countb+=1        
    plt.plot(x1, y1,z1, c=color)
    
plt.show()

if max(counta, countb) ==counta:
    prediction= "is Author A"
elif max(counta, countb) ==countb:
    prediction= "is Author B"
else: prediction = "cannot be determined"
    
print(f'Using a value of k={k}, we can predict that the Unknown Author  "{prediction}"' )

plt.legend(loc="best")

    x1 =[x[10],neighborsa[i][1]]
    y1 = [y[10], neighborsa[i][2]]
    z1 = [z[10], neighborsa[i][3]] 
    if neighborsa[i][4] == "Author A":
        color = "r" 
        counta1+=1
    else:
        color = "b"
        countb1+=1        
    plt.plot(x1, y1,z1, c=color)

plt.show()

else: prediction = "cannot be determined"

Observation and Conclusion¶

The KNN classification was used to determine the authors of two literary works (Unknown A and Unknown B) from sample of five written works each from two known authors.
From the results, we can conclude that using a k value of k=5 and k=7, Author A is the author of Unknown A and Author B is the author of Unknown B.
